本屆杜聰明獎二位得獎者簡介
※ Prof. Dr. –Ing. Rainer Waser
Institut für Werkstoffe der Elektrotechnik 2(IWE2), RWTH Aachen University(由交通大學電子工程系曾俊元教授提名)
Rainer Waser is Professor at the faculty for Electrical Engineering and Information Technology at the RWTH Aachen University and director at the Peter Grunberg Institute at the Forschungszentrum Julich (FZI), Germany.
In 1984, he received his PhD in Physical chemistry from the University of Darmstadt, and worked at the Philips Research Laboratory, Aachen, until he was appointed professor in 1992. His research group is focused on fundamental aspects of electronic materials and on such integrated with major semiconductor industries in Europe, the US, and the Far East. He has organized international conferences and has published about 560 technical papers. Since 2003, he has been the coordinator of the research program on nanoelectronic systems within the Germany national research centres in the Helmholtz Association. In 2007, he has been co-founder of the Julich-Aaschen Research Alliance, section Fundamentals of Funture Information Technology (JARA-FIT). He received numerous awards, including Gottfried-Wilhelm-Leibniz Prize(2013) and Tsungming Tu Award(2014).
※ Prof. Dr. Claudia Felser
Max Planck Institute for Chemical Physics of Solids(由臺灣大學凝態科學研究中心林昭吟研究員提名)
Prof. Claudia Felser studied chemistry and physics at the University of Cologne (Germany) and completed her doctorate in physical chemistry there in 1994. After postdoctoral fellowships at the MPI in Stuttgart and the CNRS in Nantes (France), she joined the University of Mainz and became a full professor at the University of Mainz (Germany) in 2003. She was a visiting scientist at Princeton University (USA) in 1999 and at Stanford University in 2009/2010 and a visiting professor at the University of Caen (France). In Dec. 2011, she became director at the Max Planck Institute for Chemical Physics of Solids in Dresden (Germany). She was the chair of the research group “New Materials with High Spin Polarization” and the director of the Graduate School of Excellence “Materials Science in Mainz” of the German Science Foundation from 2007-2012. She is a fellow of the American Physical Society and the Institute of Physics, London.
Her recent research focuses on the rational design of new materials for spintronics and energy technologies such as solar cells, thermoelectric materials, topological insulators and superconductors. She has published more than 300 papers, and has given more than 150 invited talks. Especially during the recent years her papers became highly cited, more than 9000 times.
The main reason for the nomination and eventually becoming the grantee of Tsungming Tu award is her recent achievement on Heusler compounds, a class of materials with many outstanding properties ranging from the half metals for spintronics to the multifunctional topological insulators for future quantum computing.
